headline: AMD to lay off 4% of its workforce as part of AI realignment
summary: Advanced Micro Devices (AMD) shares are in focus after the chipmaker announced it would be laying off 4% of its global workforce, equivalent to 1,000 workers. Market Domination's Julie Hyman and Josh Lipton break down what the news means for the company as it works to compete in the AI chip market dominated by Nvidia (NVDA). To watch more expert insights and analysis on the latest market action, check out more Market Domination here. This post was written by Naomi Buchanan.

headline: AMD to Cut Jobs. The Stock Is Dropping.
summary: Advanced Micro Devices  stock was down Wednesday following a report that said the chipmaking company plans on cutting 4% of its global workforce.  AMD  said on Wednesday that it’s cutting jobs to align its recourses with its largest growth opportunities, according to a report by The Wall Street Journal.  According to the company’s 10-K from Jan. 31, AMD ended 2023 with approximately 26,000 employees in its global workforce.

headline: AMD to cut 4% of global workforce as it focuses on AI chip development
summary: AMD is regarded as the closest rival to Nvidia in the lucrative market for chips that form the brains of complex data centers that can process the large mounds of data used by generative AI technology like OpenAI's ChatGPT.  Revenue in AMD's data center segment, which houses its AI graphics processors, jumped more than two-fold in the September quarter.  Analysts expect the data center unit to grow 98% in 2024, outpacing expected total revenue growth of 13%, according to an average of estimates compiled by LSEG.
